    "id": "778",
    "title": "Why Weight Training Causes Weight Gain?",
    "category": "General",
    "subType": "Gyan",
    "mediaType": "static",
    "videoUrl": null,
    "videoType": null,
    "youtubeId": null,
    "imageUrl": null,
    "descriptionPlain": "After seeing reels on importance of weight lifting at 40, I started it too. \n\nI was shocked to see a weight gain as my goal was to lose weight. \n\nWhy Weight Training Causes Weight Gain? \n\n1. **Muscle Mass Increase**: Muscle tissue is denser & weighs more than fat, so as you gain muscle, your weight might increase even if you're losing fat. \n\n2. **Improved Muscle Glycogen Storage**: \nGlycogen binds with water, leading to a temporary increase in weight due to water retention.\n\n3. **Enhanced Protein Synthesis**: \nAfter strength training, your body enters a state of increased protein synthesis, which repairs and grows muscle fibers. This process contributes to muscle hypertrophy (growth).\n \n \nWhats the best way then to lose weight? \n\n- **Weight Training**: Focuses on building muscle and strength. It's excellent for body composition changes, increasing muscle mass, and boosting metabolism.\n \n- **Cardio**: Effective for burning calories and fat. It improves cardiovascular health and helps create a calorie deficit, essential for weight and fat loss.\n\n### Key Takeaway:\n\n**If you want to lose weight, start with cardio exercises to burn calories and shed fat. Once you achieve your desired weight loss, incorporate strength training to build and maintain muscle mass. This approach ensures long-term results and a toned physique.**\n\n(Weight loss, strength training, muscle loss, protein intake)",
    "tags": [
      "StrengthTraining",
      "MuscleGain",
      "WeightLossJourney",
      "FitnessGoals",
      "CardioWorkout",
      "HealthyLifestyle",
      "NutritionistTips"
    ],
