    "id": "533",
    "title": "Brown rice / White rice?",
    "category": "Diabetes",
    "subType": "Gyan",
    "mediaType": "static",
    "videoUrl": null,
    "videoType": null,
    "youtubeId": null,
    "imageUrl": null,
    "descriptionPlain": "The battle between Brown Rice & White Rice Continues to Be Legendary! 🌾\nHere are some facts about both of them. \n\n👉 White Rice:\n\n• While white rice does offer some Vitamin B1 & B3, the milling & polishing process strips away much of its fiber.\n• It’s low in potassium & contains significantly less manganese and iron.\n• Having polished white rice regularly may elevate the risk of high blood sugars, insulin spikes & weight gain. \n\n👉 Brown Rice:\n\n- An excellent source of vitamins B1 & B3.\n- Packed with dietary fiber & potassium.\n- It is heart-friendly & rich in manganese making it a healthy choice.\n- Reduces the risk of Type 2 Diabetes & aids in controlling blood cholesterol.\n- Promotes weight loss.\n\nP.S.: You may have seen numerous reels claiming that brown rice is unhealthy due to its arsenic content. \nHowever, it’s essential to note that our ancestors regularly consumed unpolished brown rice without husk. \nThe key is to use common sense and opt for partially polished brown rice, as showcased in the reel. \nIt’s easier to cook, more flavorful, and keeps you satiated for longer periods, aiding in weight loss and blood sugar management.",
