    "id": "386",
    "title": "WHY NO POTATOES IN THE DIET 👇",
    "category": "General",
    "subType": "Gyan",
    "mediaType": "static",
    "videoUrl": null,
    "videoType": null,
    "youtubeId": null,
    "imageUrl": null,
    "descriptionPlain": "WHY NO POTATOES IN THE DIET 👇\n\nYes, potatoes in principle are not high in calories & if not fried or made into recipes like samosas, tikkis & parathas. \n\nThe reason why we avoid potatoes in diets plans is this:\nA potato in India is mostly considered a vegetable (sabzi) and is had with roti, bread, or rice. However, nutritionally, it is not a vegetable but a starch just like roti or rice. It is similar in calories to wheat rice or bread & also high in starch. \n\nFor example, 100g of potato contains almost 100 calories & in the same amount of cabbage, its only 25 calories. So, we ensure clients eat grains and cereals, that too whole grains (brown rice, jowar, multigrain) as they have high fiber, are more filling & low calorie. \n\nWe can’t give you double carbs as that is not the ideal plating for a balanced meal. So while potatoes are not bad, they can be left out while on a diet that is otherwise healthy & filling. \n\nGoing a bit deeper, if you see a traditional American meal, it has meat (steak), vegetables & either potato, bread or corn. This means their starch option is also limited to 1. \n\nHope this helped 🙂",
